{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b4eafb77-3f50-4df0-beb1-2f73dfdd5c41","content":"Your project uses **xUnit v3** with **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`). Use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nThe `~` operator means \"contains\", so this runs only tests whose fully qualified name includes `ShoppingCartTests`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da0340c5-2cbd-428c-98a2-4e132ec37d5e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is an xUnit v3 project with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, which means it uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). The filter syntax for MTP with xUnit v3 is different from VSTest.\n\nFor MTP with xUnit v3, the filter syntax uses `--treenode-filter` or `--filter` depending on the version. Let me check the xUnit v3 docs.\n\nActually, with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport=true`, `dotnet test` translates to MTP. For xUnit v3 on MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` with a path-like syntax.\n \nBut I should reconsider—when `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport=true` is set, `dotnet test --filter` still works because it gets translated to the MTP filter format. So using `dotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"` should work even though the native MTP filter is `--treenode-filter`.","outputTokens":509,"requestId":"A029:903FB:1963815:1CD2CB8:69FE8E7B"},"id":"bd3169ea-874d-47dd-9ad4-51b9bd019b9e","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:31:51.534Z","parentId":"3796a436-1afa-408e-b80e-0e8bb8f4268c"}
